<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-026-050 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 471 091</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 30 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM wins $38.5 million Air Force contract. (United States)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Contracts).andO;Topic:     Computer industryDefense contractsUnited States. Air Force.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****IBM Wins $38.5 Million Air Force Contract 10/30/91 BETHESDA, MARYLAND,U.S.A., 1991 OCT 30 (NB)  -- IBM has announced that it has been awarded theCommand and Data Processing (Candamp;DP) contract by the U.S.andP;  Air Force with workto begin on November 1 in Santa Clara, California and Colorado Springs,Colorado.andM;The contract, with a one-year base and four one-year options, has a value of$38.3 million for the first year.andP;  Under its terms, a team led by IBM willprovide systems engineering, software and data base development andmaintenance, test and integration, operations support, hardware maintenanceand future architecture design for the Command and Control Segment (CCS) ofthe Air Force Satellite Control Network (AFSCN), Sunnyvale, California.andM;The IBM team is comprised of Unisys Defense Systems, Litton, Harris, ComputerSciences Corporation, TRW and Scitor.andP;  IBM's responsibility under thecontract, will include program management, systems engineering, softwaredevelopment and maintenance, operations support and commercial hardwaremaintenance.andP;  Unisys will contribute network level systems engineering, testand integration.andP;  Litton will supply data base and software development andmaintenance and operations support and Harris will oversee the hardwaremaintenance and development.andP;  TRW will be responsible for systems engineeringand Scitor will handle systems engineering and integration support.andM;IBM's announcement of the award stressed its history in working with the AirForce on related projects, saying: &quot;IBM's work on the upgrade andmodernization of the AFSCN began in 1980 with the AirandM;Force award of the Data System Modernization contract.andP;   In 1986,andM;the Air Force extended IBM's role with the award of the Command and ControlSustaining Engineering contract, which has one six-month option remainingbefore contract completion.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19911030/Press Contact: J. WilliamPrater, IBM, 301-493-1359)</TEXT></DOC>